WE pass now to the consideration of the personal poems of Catullus, in which he has immortalized, by truthsully recording‚ his sincere affecffions, passionate love, genuine hatreds, clear wit, and hearty merriment.

It was truly felt at this period, by all who were not content to pass their lives in lethargy, that there was only one place on earth where active existence was possible to a man 3 that it was better to struggle and starve at Rome than hatten on the pastures of all the rest of the world. There, and there alone, could be found news, amusement, politica] agitation, society—- 'in a word, a life worth the trouble of living. How much more enjoyment than could be afforded by the stalled ox of provincial dulness was promised to him- self by Catullus, when he invited his friend to dine with him off wit and a bare cupboard, in these lines:—

‘ You shall dine nobly at my table, Fabullus, in a few days, granting your stars are favourable, if you bring a noble and ample dinner with you—sunny maiden, and wine, and salt.
